div.p:
In this study, it was demonstrated that the DMF-MS platform can be used for the detection and identification of CWA simulants, potentially applicable to CWAs with some modifications of the protocol and materials. For the purification and extraction of CWA simulants, an MB-based diol-SPE was constructed. As previously demonstrated (Lafreniere et al.

 2015

), MB-based SPE, particularly on a DMF device, can be readily applied to the purification, enrichment, and extraction of small molecules such as CWA simulants. In particular, on-chip GC-MS sensitivity significantly increased, for example, MDLs for DPGME, DMMP, TEP, MeSA, and DEP: 2.96, 1.12, 0.018, 0.76, and 0.002 μg/mL (

 on

-

 chip

) versus 7.4, 2.5, 7.3, 7.6, and 2.0 μg/mL (

 off

-

 chip

). The MDLs determined in this study can be improved further by using a set of suitable SPE sorbent materials, as each simulant has its own high-binding affinity sorbent material. Because the simultaneous movement control of several droplets is possible, it can be envisaged that multiple on-chip SPEs, each of which has a different sorbent coating on the MB surface, could be made on a larger DMF devices with more electrodes. The protocol shown in this study clearly demonstrates that the CWA analyses can be automated on the DMF-MS platform to minimize human involvement, which is essential in modern mobile laboratory practice. It is also notable that the full automation is not accomplished yet, and the current setup still requires human intervention, e.g., injection of samples, collection of purified/enriched analytes, and injection of the analytes onto the analysis system by analysts. The first two steps, such as injection and collection, can be readily automated using a synchronized syringe pump system, and the final step, i.e., the injection of the anlaytes onto the analysis system, is expected to be automated soon. For example, the so-called e-MALDI method, in which a mixture of the analytes and MALDI matrix was dried on the DMF chip with substantially smaller and more homogeneous sample spots, is recently published (Kudina et al.

 2016

). Also, the interfacing of the DMF chip and GC-MS is expected to be made soon since the interfacing of the DMF technology with liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry (DMF-LC/MS) is already accomplished (Choi et al.

 2016

).
